{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-js","path":"/how-to-install-and-use-node-js-and-npm-mac-and-windows/","webpackCompilationHash":"","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>In order to use almost any development tools based in JavaScript, you'll need to know how to use npm and Node.js. <a href=\"/getting-started-with-gulp/\">Gulp</a>, <a href=\"/getting-started-with-grunt-and-sass/\">Grunt</a>, and Webpack are a few examples of popular technologies you may have heard of that require a knowledge of the Node ecosystem.</p>\n<p>I find myself writing about this over and over again in the prerequisites of an article I've begun to write. I'd prefer to write one definitive guide to refer to in the future, so here it is.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://github.com/taniarascia/node-test\">View on GitHub</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h4 id=\"prerequisites\"><a href=\"#prerequisites\" aria-label=\"prerequisites permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Prerequisites</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"/how-to-use-the-command-line-for-apple-macos-and-linux/\">Basic command line proficiency</a>. Don't skip this step! If you don't know how to use the command line, you'll be fighting an uphill battle. The provided tutorial has everything you need to know.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4 id=\"goals\"><a href=\"#goals\" aria-label=\"goals permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Goals</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Learn what Node.js and npm are</li>\n<li>Set up Node.js and npm on Windows and Mac</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"what-is-nodejs\"><a href=\"#what-is-nodejs\" aria-label=\"what is nodejs permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>What is Node.js?</h2>\n<p>JavaScript is a <strong>client-side</strong> programming language, which means it’s processed in the browser. With the advent of <a href=\"https://nodejs.org/en/\">Node.js</a>, JavaScript can also be used as a <strong>server-side</strong> language.</p>\n<h2 id=\"what-is-npm\"><a href=\"#what-is-npm\" aria-label=\"what is npm permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>What is npm?</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.npmjs.com/\">npm</a> doesn't stand for <strong>Node Package Manager*</strong>, which means it’s the tool to connect to the repository containing all the Node.js programs, plugins, modules and so on.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>*npm actually does not stand for \"Node Package Manager\" but essentially that's what it is and does, so most people refer to it that way.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<h2 id=\"local-vs-global\"><a href=\"#local-vs-global\" aria-label=\"local vs global permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Local vs. Global</h2>\n<p>This is the most confusing concept to understand at first, so it's important to let this settle in. Traditionally, you're used to globally installing any sort of program or software on your computer. If you want Spotify, you'll download Spotify, and then it will be available to you.</p>\n<p>With npm, you will have some global installs, but mostly everything will be done on a local project basis, meaning you'll have to install everything you need for each project in its own directory. If you want to have a project running Gulp and Sass, you'll create a directory, with a new npm install.</p>\n<p>For future reference, any global installations will have the <code class=\"language-text\">-g</code> flag.</p>\n<h2 id=\"installation-on-windows\"><a href=\"#installation-on-windows\" aria-label=\"installation on windows permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Installation on Windows</h2>\n<p>Installing everything on Windows is a breeze.</p>\n<h3 id=\"install-nodejs-and-npm\"><a href=\"#install-nodejs-and-npm\" aria-label=\"install nodejs and npm permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Install Node.js and npm</h3>\n<p>Node.js and npm can be installed from a download link. Go to the <a href=\"https://nodejs.org/en/download/\">Node installation page</a>, and download the Node installer. I have a 64-bit Windows 10 OS, so I chose that one.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 495px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/e2c6dffbf59d1a2fd89130af04164eb1/1bacc/node.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 78.18181818181817%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"node\"\n        title=\"node\"\n        src=\"/static/e2c6dffbf59d1a2fd89130af04164eb1/1bacc/node.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/e2c6dffbf59d1a2fd89130af04164eb1/09a7d/node.jpg 213w,\n/static/e2c6dffbf59d1a2fd89130af04164eb1/28bbc/node.jpg 425w,\n/static/e2c6dffbf59d1a2fd89130af04164eb1/1bacc/node.jpg 495w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 495px) 100vw, 495px\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>Once it's done, you can test to see both node and npm functioning by opening PowerShell (or any shell) and typing <code class=\"language-text\">node -v</code> and <code class=\"language-text\">npm -v</code>, which will check the version number.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 526px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/d889c946f42836b505c7a9f482453247/597fc/powershell.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 54.372623574144484%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"powershell\"\n        title=\"powershell\"\n        src=\"/static/d889c946f42836b505c7a9f482453247/597fc/powershell.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/d889c946f42836b505c7a9f482453247/09a7d/powershell.jpg 213w,\n/static/d889c946f42836b505c7a9f482453247/28bbc/powershell.jpg 425w,\n/static/d889c946f42836b505c7a9f482453247/597fc/powershell.jpg 526w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 526px) 100vw, 526px\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>All set.</p>\n<h2 id=\"installation-on-a-mac-or-linux\"><a href=\"#installation-on-a-mac-or-linux\" aria-label=\"installation on a mac or linux permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Installation on a Mac or Linux</h2>\n<p>In order to install everything on a Mac, we'll be running commands in Terminal.app, and Linux distributions vary.</p>\n<h3 id=\"install-nodejs-and-npm-1\"><a href=\"#install-nodejs-and-npm-1\" aria-label=\"install nodejs and npm 1 permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Install Node.js and npm</h3>\n<p>We’re going to use <a href=\"https://github.com/creationix/nvm\">Node Version Manager (nvm)</a> to install Node.js and npm.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\"><span class=\"token function\">curl</span> -o- https://raw.githubusercontent.com/creationix/nvm/v0.33.1/install.sh <span class=\"token operator\">|</span> <span class=\"token function\">bash</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>Open the <code class=\"language-text\">~/.bash_profile</code> file, and make sure <code class=\"language-text\">source ~/.bashrc</code> is written in there somewhere. Restart the terminal.</p>\n<p>Run the install command.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\">nvm <span class=\"token function\">install</span> node</code></pre></div>\n<p>Run the use command.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\">nvm use node</code></pre></div>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"terminal\"><pre class=\"language-terminal\"><code class=\"language-terminal\">Now using node v8.2.0 (npm v5.3.0)</code></pre></div>\n<p>Now that Node.js and npm are installed, test them by typing <code class=\"language-text\">node -v</code> and <code class=\"language-text\">npm -v</code>.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 850px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/42a2e888eaa4e8581605e8a2914be8e4/2b2cf/term-1.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 64.88340192043897%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"term 1\"\n        title=\"term 1\"\n        src=\"/static/42a2e888eaa4e8581605e8a2914be8e4/4d3f1/term-1.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/42a2e888eaa4e8581605e8a2914be8e4/0cb30/term-1.png 213w,\n/static/42a2e888eaa4e8581605e8a2914be8e4/a67b6/term-1.png 425w,\n/static/42a2e888eaa4e8581605e8a2914be8e4/4d3f1/term-1.png 850w,\n/static/42a2e888eaa4e8581605e8a2914be8e4/bfdc0/term-1.png 1275w,\n/static/42a2e888eaa4e8581605e8a2914be8e4/2b2cf/term-1.png 1458w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 850px) 100vw, 850px\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>All set.</p>\n<h2 id=\"create-a-project\"><a href=\"#create-a-project\" aria-label=\"create a project permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Create a Project</h2>\n<p>At this point, you're set to start setting up Gulp, Webpack, Browserify, or whatever your aim is. We can also create a simple project to test that everything is working properly.</p>\n<h3 id=\"initialize-project\"><a href=\"#initialize-project\" aria-label=\"initialize project permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Initialize Project</h3>\n<p>Navigate to the directory in which you want your project to exist - in my case, <strong>sites/node-test</strong>.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\"><span class=\"token builtin class-name\">cd</span> sites/node-test</code></pre></div>\n<p>Now initalize a new project with npm.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\"><span class=\"token function\">npm</span> init</code></pre></div>\n<p>The following will pop up in the terminal, and prompt you for a few</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"terminal\"><pre class=\"language-terminal\"><code class=\"language-terminal\">This utility will walk you through creating a package.json file.\nIt only covers the most common items, and tries to guess sensible defaults.\n\nSee `npm help json` for definitive documentation on these fields\nand exactly what they do.\n\nUse `npm install &lt;pkg&gt;` afterwards to install a package and\nsave it as a dependency in the package.json file.</code></pre></div>\n<p>First, it will ask for a package name.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\">node-test</code></pre></div>\n<p>Version number.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"text\"><pre class=\"language-text\"><code class=\"language-text\">1.0.0</code></pre></div>\n<p>Description.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"text\"><pre class=\"language-text\"><code class=\"language-text\">Creating my first &quot;Hello, World!&quot; Node project.</code></pre></div>\n<p>The rest you can just press enter and skip. Now you'll notice we have a <strong>package.json</strong> file that contains all the information we entered.</p>\n<div class=\"filename\">package.json</div>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"js\"><pre class=\"language-js\"><code class=\"language-js\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n  <span class=\"token string\">\"name\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> <span class=\"token string\">\"node-test\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span>\n  <span class=\"token string\">\"version\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> <span class=\"token string\">\"1.0.0\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span>\n  <span class=\"token string\">\"description\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> <span class=\"token string\">\"Creating my first \\\"Hello, World!\\\" Node project.\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span>\n  <span class=\"token string\">\"main\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> <span class=\"token string\">\"index.js\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span>\n  <span class=\"token string\">\"scripts\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n    <span class=\"token string\">\"test\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> <span class=\"token string\">\"echo \\\"Error: no test specified\\\" &amp;&amp; exit 1\"</span>\n  <span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span>\n  <span class=\"token string\">\"author\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> <span class=\"token string\">\"Tania Rascia\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span>\n  <span class=\"token string\">\"license\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> <span class=\"token string\">\"ISC\"</span>\n<span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>A <strong>package.json</strong> is a file that contains metadata about the project, and handles the dependencies (additional software and modules) of the project.</p>\n<p>Now, we're going to install our first dependency - a very important and useful package called <strong>left-pad</strong>, which will add white space to the left side of a string, adding up to a number.</p>\n<p>For example, writing this:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"js\"><pre class=\"language-js\"><code class=\"language-js\"><span class=\"token function\">leftPad</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token string\">'String'</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token number\">10</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>Will output this:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"terminal\"><pre class=\"language-terminal\"><code class=\"language-terminal\">console</code></pre></div>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"js\"><pre class=\"language-js\"><code class=\"language-js\">String</code></pre></div>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.npmjs.com/package/left-pad\">left-pad</a> is a package on npm, which as we stated previously contains the registry for all publicly available packages.</p>\n<h3 id=\"install-dependencies\"><a href=\"#install-dependencies\" aria-label=\"install dependencies permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Install dependencies</h3>\n<p>To install a dependency with npm, we use the command <code class=\"language-text\">npm install dependency-name-here</code>. Now, simply running <code class=\"language-text\">npm install</code> will download the dependency, but it won't save it to the project. Since we've already created our <strong>package.json</strong>, we'll use the flag <code class=\"language-text\">--save</code> to install the dependency <em>and</em> add it to <strong>package.json</strong>.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\"><span class=\"token function\">npm</span> <span class=\"token function\">install</span> left-pad --save</code></pre></div>\n<p>As long as you ran this command inside the project directory, it will successfully install the dependency by creating a <strong>node_modules</strong> directory. It will also create a <strong>package-lock.json</strong> file, which we can ignore. Finally, it updated our <strong>package.json</strong> file with a new line.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"js\"><pre class=\"language-js\"><code class=\"language-js\"><span class=\"token string\">\"dependencies\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n  <span class=\"token string\">\"left-pad\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> <span class=\"token string\">\"^1.1.3\"</span>\n<span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>Now the project recognizes the left-pad dependency as existing</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>You can also run <code class=\"language-text\">npm install --save-dev</code> to specify that the dependency will only be used for development (not production) purposes.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<h3 id=\"run-node-in-the-terminal\"><a href=\"#run-node-in-the-terminal\" aria-label=\"run node in the terminal permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Run Node in the terminal</h3>\n<p>Let's create <strong>index.js</strong> in the root of our directory. This is everything you should have now:</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 790px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/0999a65c5c9c2a2d7eff5cd1d5ec7b44/30398/Screen-Shot-2017-07-21-at-5.28.47-PM.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 21.51898734177215%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Screen Shot 2017 07 21 at 5 28 47 PM\"\n        title=\"Screen Shot 2017 07 21 at 5 28 47 PM\"\n        src=\"/static/0999a65c5c9c2a2d7eff5cd1d5ec7b44/30398/Screen-Shot-2017-07-21-at-5.28.47-PM.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/0999a65c5c9c2a2d7eff5cd1d5ec7b44/0cb30/Screen-Shot-2017-07-21-at-5.28.47-PM.png 213w,\n/static/0999a65c5c9c2a2d7eff5cd1d5ec7b44/a67b6/Screen-Shot-2017-07-21-at-5.28.47-PM.png 425w,\n/static/0999a65c5c9c2a2d7eff5cd1d5ec7b44/30398/Screen-Shot-2017-07-21-at-5.28.47-PM.png 790w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 790px) 100vw, 790px\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>For future reference, don't bother looking in the <strong>node_modules</strong> rabbit hole. It will get really overwhelming with bigger projects.</p>\n<p>In order to use a dependency, we use <code class=\"language-text\">require()</code> and put it in a variable, like so:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"js\"><pre class=\"language-js\"><code class=\"language-js\"><span class=\"token keyword\">const</span> leftPad <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token function\">require</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token string\">'left-pad'</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>This will be the entirety of our <strong>index.js</strong> file, in which we require left-pad, run a <code class=\"language-text\">leftPad()</code> function, and send it to the console.</p>\n<div class=\"filename\">index.js</div>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"js\"><pre class=\"language-js\"><code class=\"language-js\"><span class=\"token keyword\">const</span> leftPad <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token function\">require</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token string\">'left-pad'</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span> <span class=\"token comment\">// Require left pad</span>\n<span class=\"token keyword\">const</span> output <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token function\">leftPad</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token string\">'Hello, World!'</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> <span class=\"token number\">15</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span> <span class=\"token comment\">// Define output</span>\n\n<span class=\"token comment\">// Send output to the console</span>\nconsole<span class=\"token punctuation\">.</span><span class=\"token function\">log</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>output<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>Since Node.js is not recognized by the browser, we'll be testing this in the console. In your shell, run the <code class=\"language-text\">node</code> command followed by the filename in the root of your project.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\">node index.js</code></pre></div>\n<p>If everything went well, you should have printed <code class=\"language-text\">Hello, World!</code> to the console, with two spaces on the left.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"terminal\"><pre class=\"language-terminal\"><code class=\"language-terminal\">Hello, World!</code></pre></div>\n<h2 id=\"conclusion\"><a href=\"#conclusion\" aria-label=\"conclusion permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Conclusion</h2>\n<p>In this tutorial, we learned the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>What Node.js is</li>\n<li>What npm is</li>\n<li>How to install Node.js and npm on Windows or Mac</li>\n<li>How to make a local project</li>\n<li>How to install a dependency with npm</li>\n<li>How to run a file using a <strong>node_modules</strong> dependency in a shell</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If you got lost at any point, <a href=\"https://github.com/taniarascia/node-test\">view the source on GitHub</a>.</p>\n<p>With this knowledge, you're ready to start using Gulp, Grunt, Webpack, Browserify, or anything else that depends on Node.js or npm.</p>","timeToRead":7,"excerpt":"In order to use almost any development tools based in JavaScript, you'll need to know how to use npm and Node.js. Gulp, Grunt, and Webpack…","frontmatter":{"title":"How to Install and Use Node.js and npm (Mac, Windows, Linux)","thumbnail":{"childImageSharp":{"fixed":{"base64":"data:image/png;base64,","width":150,"height":150,"src":"/static/517c02bd875932e2a959488763695b28/4148e/node.png","srcSet":"/static/517c02bd875932e2a959488763695b28/4148e/node.png 1x"}}},"slug":"how-to-install-and-use-node-js-and-npm-mac-and-windows","date":"2017-07-21T00:00:00.000Z","categories":["Code"],"tags":["javascript","node","npm"],"template":"post"},"fields":{"slug":"/how-to-install-and-use-node-js-and-npm-mac-and-windows/","date":"2017-07-21T00:00:00.000Z"}}},"pageContext":{"isCreatedByStatefulCreatePages":false,"slug":"/how-to-install-and-use-node-js-and-npm-mac-and-windows/"}}}